						<summary><ptr target="bib:IAR2003-2004"/> (p. 367): <quote>Inscibed on the granite slab, used as the step stone at the entrance of Śrī Śivasubrahmaṇya Svāmin temple at Ālantūr, Tambaram Taluk, District Kanchipuram. This slab might have been brought from a dilapidated Jaina <foreign>paḷḷi</foreign> at Māṅkāṭu (near Kuṉṟattūr) and laid here when this temple was constructed, probably in the 18th-19th centuries. The inscription contains the information that the daughter of one Amarnilaiyar
							of Paripandatturai Paricai in
							Āṟkkāṭṭukkūṟṟam who was a
							disciple of Anandavirakkuravar
							gifted paddy for offering at
							the <foreign>avi</foreign> (<foreign>havis</foreign>) and a plate
							for holding the offerings,
							at the Teruvarantanam at
							Māṅkāṭu in Māṅkāṭunāṭu in
							Puliyūkkōṭṭam. 875 AD Pallava Kampavikramavarman</quote>.<!--update diacritics--></summary>
					</msContents>
